- "Concentration of initiatives per person" is calculated as the number of prevention initiatives multiplied by the population density of the district;
- "Notably higher than the national average" means the state's average initiative density is greater than the overall average initiative density across all states.

- The logarithmic crime rate is calculated by taking the natural logarithm of the crime rate and then exponentiating the sum of these logarithms;
- The crime rate is defined as the number of crimes per 100,000 people;
- The state with the highest logarithmic crime rate is the one that ranks first in this specialized metric.
